Filter the scrobbles you tweet
Here's the code. The original project ran in Eclipse
with the Google App Engine plugin.

## Build

Requires Java 17 and Maven.

    mvn package -DskipTests

## Running Tests

### Unit tests

    mvn test

### End-to-end tests (Playwright)

Prerequisites:
- Docker (image must be built first)
- Node.js
- Google Cloud SDK with the beta and Datastore emulator components installed:

      gcloud components install beta cloud-datastore-emulator

One-time setup:

    docker build -t scrobblefilter .
    cd playwright
    npm install
    npx playwright install chromium

Run all tests (Playwright automatically starts the Datastore emulator, the app
in Docker, and a Last.fm mock server before running):

    cd playwright
    npm test

Run smoke tests only (no Datastore emulator needed):

    cd playwright
    npm run test:smoke

See playwrightplan.md for a full description of the test scenarios and
infrastructure setup.

## Deploy (Cloud Run)

The app runs on Cloud Run in project `scrobblefilter`, region `us-central1`,
as the service `scrobblefilter`. Images live in Artifact Registry at
`us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/scrobblefilter/scrobblefilter/app`.

Prerequisites: Google Cloud SDK authenticated as a project owner/editor
(`gcloud auth login`), with the project set (`gcloud config set project scrobblefilter`).

1. Build the image in the cloud and push it to Artifact Registry (Cloud Build
   uses the Dockerfile, so no local Docker is required):

       gcloud builds submit --tag us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/scrobblefilter/scrobblefilter/app:latest

2. Tag the image with the git SHA for traceability (optional but recommended):

       gcloud artifacts docker tags add \
         us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/scrobblefilter/scrobblefilter/app:latest \
         us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/scrobblefilter/scrobblefilter/app:$(git rev-parse --short HEAD)

3. Deploy. The service's existing secret bindings (`MIGRATE_TOKEN`,
   `CRON_TOKEN`) are preserved automatically, so they don't need to be
   re-specified on a routine redeploy:

       gcloud run deploy scrobblefilter \
         --image us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/scrobblefilter/scrobblefilter/app:latest \
         --region us-central1 \
         --quiet

4. Verify the new revision:

       SVC_URL=$(gcloud run services describe scrobblefilter --region=us-central1 --format='value(status.url)')
       curl -s -o /dev/null -w 'welcome: %{http_code}\n' "$SVC_URL/hello/welcome"
       # admin endpoint must reject an unauthenticated request:
       curl -s -o /dev/null -w 'no-token: %{http_code}\n' "$SVC_URL/hello/admin/migrate"

   Expect `welcome: 200` and `no-token: 403`.

The admin/cron secrets were created once with `gcloud secrets create
migrate-token` / `cron-token` and first bound to the service with
`gcloud run deploy ... --update-secrets MIGRATE_TOKEN=migrate-token:latest,CRON_TOKEN=cron-token:latest`.
Only repeat that `--update-secrets` step if a binding is removed or a new
secret is added.

### Data migration (one-time, only when the entity schema changes)

`/hello/admin/migrate` re-keys legacy entities and is idempotent. It is gated
by the `MIGRATE_TOKEN` secret. It is not part of a routine code deploy — run it
only when a schema migration is required:

    TOKEN=$(gcloud secrets versions access latest --secret=migrate-token)
    SVC_URL=$(gcloud run services describe scrobblefilter --region=us-central1 --format='value(status.url)')
    curl -s -H "X-Admin-Token: $TOKEN" "${SVC_URL}/hello/admin/migrate" -w '\nHTTP %{http_code}\n'
